Introduction_text1 <- "
The discovery of penicillin in 1928 marked a monumental advancement in
medicine, revolutionizing our society and economy by saving countless
lives. However, the emergence of resistance among many pathogens to
commonly used antibiotics, coupled with a dearth of new antimicrobial
therapies, now poses a serious threat. This threat harkens back to the
era before antibiotics, where even minor wounds and infections could
inflict significant harm and, tragically, death. Consequently, routine
medical procedures carry an elevated risk.
<br/><br/>
The danger is palpable, with 35,000 people in Europe succumbing to
infections caused by bacteria resistant to antibiotics each year. In
fact, the burden of infections displaying bacterial resistance to
antibiotics in Europe is comparable to the impacts of influenza,
tuberculosis, and HIV/AIDS combined.
<br/><br/>
Antimicrobial resistance stands as the quintessential illustration of a
'One Health' challenge. It is now widely accepted that human and animal
health are intricately intertwined. Since diseases can move between
humans and animals, it is imperative to address these issues
holistically in both domains. Moreover, there is a growing
acknowledgment of the environment's role in fostering the emergence and
dissemination of antimicrobial resistance, particularly in areas at high
risk, exposed to the discharge of human, animal, and industrial waste
streams.
<br/><br/>
Considering the significant and interconnected aspects of antimicrobial
resistance in the realms of human health, animal health, and the
environment, it becomes imperative to adopt a One Health approach when
tackling this multifaceted problem.
<br/><br/>
<b>A National Action Plan </b>
<br/><br/>
The NAP-AMR has been developed to clarify and establish mechanisms for
multi-sectoral cooperation. Its primary aim is to promote effective
coordination among partners, presenting a common vision and uniting the
various initiatives within Belgium. This plan is structured around two
central challenges: (i)<b>preventing and controlling infections</b>, thus
reducing the transmission of micro-organisms and resistance, and (ii)
<b>ensuring the prudent use of antimicrobials</b>.
<br/><br/>
To meet these challenges effectively, it is imperative to gain a
comprehensive understanding of the situation in Belgium. This includes
assessing the impact of implemented measures and taking appropriate
action based on these evaluations. While Belgium has had effective
surveillance systems in place for antimicrobial consumption (AMC) and
antimicrobial resistance (AMR) for several years (as depicted in Figure
1), there has been a lack of a clear, overarching view of developments
across different sectors.
<br/><br/>
Following the 'One Health' approach, the BELMAP report not only aims to
present the primary available data but also facilitates an analysis of
the relationship between consumption and resistance within and across
various sectors. This approach is crucial for a more holistic and
integrated response to antimicrobial resistance, aligning human, animal,
and environmental dimensions.
"


