bc_ec_text <- "In cattle, <i>E. coli</i> is most often associated with disease in calves, with observed pathology varying according to the bacterial strain. Intestinal overgrowth of <i>E. coli</i> can be associated with diarrhea and poor digestion in cattle. This is most frequently caused by insufficient colostrum intake and subsequent poor immunity and nutritional errors and is most often seen in intensively fed cattle. One of the more severe manifestations of <i>E. coli</i> infections is colisepticemia, this is most often observed in immunocompromised individuals – either in young calves due to insufficient colostrum intake and failure of passive immune transfer, or in older immunocompromised individuals, most often suffering from severe comorbidities. 
<br/><br/>
Between 2014 and 2022, 15,342 <i>E. coli</i> isolates were isolated from the faeces of diseased cattle and tested for antibiotic sensitivity. As shown in Figure 40, the majority of isolates were found to be resistant to this combination (8,917/15,342 samples from 2014-2022, 58.1%). By contrast, isolates showed low resistance to aminoglycosides or colistin during the study period, with an average of 6.5% and 4.5% of the isolates resistant to apramycin and colistin, respectively in the total period studied from 2015–2021.
<br/><br/>
A significant limitation of this dataset is the grouping of all cattle data together, independent of host age or production system, with for example calves from veal or dairy farms experiencing varying challenges and thus potentially different disease and resistance profiles. We do, for instance, observe that resistance profiles of bovine commensal <i>E. coli</i>  (see section 8.2) vary between adult cattle and young veal calves <a href='https://www.favv-afsca.be/productionanimale/antibioresistance/resultats/#sciensano'>[58]</a>. Indeed, the recommended treatment for pathogenic <i>E. coli</i> causing digestive disorders varies by host age, with the combination therapy of trimethoprim and sulfonamide noted the first line treatment for diarrhoea in older cattle (where low trimethoprim-sulphonamide resistance is expected), while prevention is the preferred first line for diarrhoea in younger cattle, with trimethoprim and sulfonamide combinations listed as a potential second line treatment with many other antimicrobials, as high resistance may be expected in this setting. "

bc_ec_fig_leg <- "<b>Figure:</b> Evolution of resistance (%) to TMP-SMX (black), colistin (green) and apramycin (blue) in <i>E. coli</i> isolated from the faeces of diseased cattle. Data source: ARSIA & DGZ "

bc_mh_text <- "<i>Mannheimia haemolytica</i> and <i>Pasteurella multocida</i> are both Gram-negative bacteria that are commensals of the bovine nasopharyngeal tract, and also associated with bovine respiratory disease (BRD) complex. BRD is a multifactorial syndrome for which no single pathogen is responsible, but rather it results from the interaction of the host’s immune system with respiratory pathogens (bacterial, viral, parasitic or fungal) and environmental influences (e.g. ammonia, dust, temperature) <a href='https://www.msdvetmanual.com/respiratory-system/bovine-respiratory-disease-complex'>[64]</a>. While it may be observed at any age, it is more common in calves, and is observed as a herd or group problem. As a multifactorial disease, the implementation of actions to reduce predisposing conditions, including potential vaccination against contributing viral pathogens, is important for reducing disease prevalence and supporting animal welfare. 
<br/><br/>
Since 2014, <i>M. haemolytica</i> isolates tested for antibacterial resistance have demonstrated low (<10%) rates of resistance to florfenicol (Figure 41), the first choice treatment according to the AMCRA guidelines <a href='https://formularium.amcra.be/58'>[65]</a>. Resistance to doxycycline, a second choice treatment option, was low from 2014 to 2017 but has since increased (highest observed value of 28.6% recorded in 2022). The rate of resistance to TMP-SMX has oscillated within the study period, but remained below 10% since 2019."

bc_mh_fig_leg <- "<b>Figure:</b> Evolution of resistance (%) to florfenicol (green), TMP-SMX (black) and doxycycline (pink) in <i>M. haemolytica</i> isolated from diseased cattle. Data source: ARSIA & DGZ"


bc_pm_text <- "<i>Mannheimia haemolytica</i> and <i>Pasteurella multocida</i> are both Gram-negative bacteria that are commensals of the bovine nasopharyngeal tract, and also associated with bovine respiratory disease (BRD) complex. BRD is a multifactorial syndrome for which no single pathogen is responsible, but rather it results from the interaction of the host’s immune system with respiratory pathogens (bacterial, viral, parasitic or fungal) and environmental influences (e.g. ammonia, dust, temperature) <a href='https://www.msdvetmanual.com/respiratory-system/bovine-respiratory-disease-complex'>[64]</a>. While it may be observed at any age, it is more common in calves, and is observed as a herd or group problem. As a multifactorial disease, the implementation of actions to reduce predisposing conditions, including potential vaccination against contributing viral pathogens, is important for reducing disease prevalence and supporting animal welfare. 
<br/><br/>
For <i>P. multocida</i>, resistance to florfenicol and to TMP-SMX are low (Figure 42), with resistance to TMP-SMX decreasing across the study period. By contrast, resistance to doxycycline has increased across the study period. Once again, the grouping of data across cattle ages and production types may be masking stratified resistance profile patterns."

bc_pm_fig_leg <- "<b>Figure:</b> Evolution of resistance (%) to florfenicol (green), TMP-SMX (black) and doxycycline (pink) in <i>P. multocida</i> isolated from diseased cattle. <b>Note y axis scale adjusted 0 - 20% to facilitate pattern visualisation.</b> Data source: ARSIA & DGZ"



# chicken pathogens

c_ec_text <- "Although many <i>E. coli</i> are non-pathogenic, avian pathogenic strains of <i>E. coli</i> can cause a variety of symptoms in chickens, varying from localized to systemic infections. Together these conditions are known as colibacillosis, and represent one of the most common causes of mortality and most economically devastating bacterial diseases for poultry farming globally <a href='https://www.msdvetmanual.com/poultry/colibacillosis/colibacillosis-in-poultry'>[66]</a>. Worryingly, <i>E. coli</i> isolated from the internal organs of diseased chickens displayed high prevalence of antimicrobial resistance against all tested antibiotics. Figure 43 depicts the rate of resistance to the recommended antibiotic treatments, with combined trimethophrim - sulphonamide representing the recommended first choice and tetracyclines as the recommended second line treatment. As drinking-water based treatments are often the only practical option within poultry farms, and given the increased oral availability of doxycycline, this is often preferred over others within the tetracycline group. Overall, the highest levels of resistance is observed against amoxicillin, followed by tetracyclines and trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole with a statistically significant increase in the prevalence of resistance over time for all antibiotics.
<br/><br/>
Very high levels of resistance are consistently observed in all three depicted antibiotics since 2020, with peak resistance to first and second line treatments observed in 2021 (60.2% and 64.7% resistant to TMP-SMX and tetracyclines respectively). Such levels of resistance might endanger the therapeutic success when treating colibacillosis with a first, second, or third line antibiotic. In terms of co-resistance, tetracyclines, amoxicillin and trimethoprim-sulphonamides are known to share the same plasmids. Co-selection by the use of one of these antimicrobial classes may therefore induce resistance to all of them.
"

c_ec_fig_leg <- "<b>Figure:</b> Evolution of resistance (%) to TMP-SMX, tetracycline and amoxicillin in <i>E. coli</i> isolated from inner organs of diseased chickens. Of note, pre-2017 the resistance to amoxicillin was based on resistance measured for ampicillin. Data source: DGZ"

c_ece_text <- "<i>Enterococcus cecorum</i> was initially considered a commensal of the gastrointestinal tract of chickens, but in recent decades has emerged as a cause of poultry morbidity and mortality, particularly in  broilers<a href='https://doi.org/10.2903/j.efsa.2022.7126'>[67]</a>. <i>E. cecorum</i> has been associated with both acute and chronic osteomyelitis, arthritis and septicemia in adult chickens. As very few isolates have been analysed each year so far, no trend analysis can be performed. AMR testing of <i>E. cecorum</i> isolates from the internal organs of diseased chickens indicates a consistently extremely high prevalence of resistance to TMP-SMX since 2014 (minimum 83.9% (26/31 isolates) in 2016, maximum 100% (27/27 isolates) in 2015). This may result in potential therapeutic failure when using this first line antibiotic to treat <i>E. cecorum</i> infections. Resistance to the other listed recommended first line therapy, doxycycline, was stable between 2014–2016, but has increased sharply since then, while resistance to ampicillin is consistently low. This increase in resistance appears at odds with antimicrobial consumption data, which indicate decreasing use of tetracyclines (doxycycline and tetracycline, expressed in BD100) since 2018 when species- specific antibiotic use was first reported. Co-selection of resistance due to the use of other antimicrobial classes may be contributing to observed resistance patterns."

