# swine pathogens

s_ec_text <- "As in other species, <i>E. coli</i> may be present in the gastrointestinal tract of healthy pigs, but can also be associated with outbreaks of diarrheal and other digestive conditions in farmed pigs. Husbandry and environmental conditions are thought to contribute to disease development, such that a series of preventative methods, over a first line antimicrobial therapy, is the preferred and recommended action to avoid disease development <a href='https://formularium.amcra.be/i/42'>[68]</a>. However, should preventative methods fail and symptoms arise, AMCRA recommends second and third choice antimicrobials – including, among others, apramycin and colistin. AMCRA does not recommend colistine as a first line antimicrobial because it is  listed as a WHO Critically Important Antimicrobial (CIA). . Figure 44 show the recorded prevalence of resistance to amoxicillin, apramycin and colistin. We see low and stable prevalence of resistance to apramycin (<5% throughout study period) and colistin (<10% throughout study period). Amoxicillin is not proposed as therapy due to the high resistance of <i>E. coli</i> to aminopenicillins and the selective pressure exerted by the use of those molecules towards the selection of ESBL-producing <i>E. coli</i>, with indeed very or extremely high observed rates of resistance across the study period (minimum 65.9% (162/242 isolates) in 2021, maximum 81.3% (334/411 isolates) in 2017).
<br/><br/>
Hemolytic <i>E. coli</i> causes diarrhea in neonatal pigs and diarrhea and edema disease in weaned pigs. Effective prevention and rapid treatment is essential as gastrointestinal disruption as a neonate can have dramatic impacts on overall production. Again, preventative methods to optimize hygiene and husbandry, as well as a maternal vaccination, are preferred to responsive antimicrobial therapy – thus AMCRA does not describe a first choice antibiotic. However, if such mechanisms fail and the conditions arise then antimicrobials such as apramycin and colistin can serve as second line therapeutic options. While a statistically significant decrease in resistance is observed for colistin (decreasing from 18% on 2014 to 8.4% on 2021), a significant increase is observed for apramycin (increasing from 3.1% in 2014 to >7% in 2021 and 2022) (Figure 45). Due to a high degree of observed resistance to trimethoprim-sulfonamides and tetracyclines, AMCRA classifies these molecules as third choice. Again, amoxicillin is not recommended by national guidelines, and the rate of resistance of <i>E. coli</i> isolates to amoxicillin remains extremely high (lower Figure).  "

