<b>Figure lower:</b>Evolution of resistance (%) to amoxicillin (dark blue), colistin (green) and apramycin (light blue) in hemolytic <i>E. coli</i> isolated from faeces of diseased swine. Of note, pre-2017 the resistance to amoxicillin was based on resistance to ampicillin. Data source: DGZ"

s_sh_text <- "<i>Staphylococcus hyicus</i> can be a normal inhabitant of porcine skin, but when toxin-producing strains penetrate the skin they can cause exudative epidermitis (Greasy Pig Disease). As very few isolates have been analysed each year so far, no trend analysis has been performed. In addition to the small sample size, as <i>S. hyicus</i> is generally associated with porcine skin infections, it should be considered that it remains unclear how accurately the resistance profile of <i>S. hyicus</i> strains isolated from porcine blood (presented here) may represent <i>S. hyicus</i> present in skin lesions.
AMCRA recommends benzylpenicillin as the first choice antimicrobial for treating exudative epidermitis. Since 2015, we consistently observe very to extremely high resistance to benzylpenicillin (minimum 55% (11/20 isolates) in 2019, maximum 95.8% (23/24 isolates) in 2021. Similarly, very high resistance is observed most years for tetracyclines (minimum 20% (2/10 isolates) in 2022, maximum 85.7% (12/14 isolates) in 2016). Such very high resistance rates make tetracyclines third choice for treating <i>S. hyicus</i> skin infections. While we observe generally lower, but still high resistance to TMP-SMX, one of the recommended second choice antibiotics for <i>S. hyicus</i> causing skin infections (minimum 0% (2/10 isolates) in 2022, maximum 35.7% (5/14 isolates) in 2016).
"

