bm_ec_text <- "Mastitis is defined as the inflammation of the mammary tissue (udder), most often in response to bacterial intramammary infection <a href='https://doi.org/10.5713/ajas.20.0156'>[69]</a>. Mastitis symptoms can range from subclinical (no clinical symptoms but detectable by for instance increased numbers of somatic cells within milk), chronic or acute and local or systemic. Bovine clinical mastitis is most commonly observed in early lactation, and is frequently caused by <i>E. coli</i>, <i>Streptococcus Agalactiae</i>, <i>Streptococcus uberis</i>  or <i>S. aureus</i> infections. Since the cure rate of mild and moderate mastitis (milk and udder symptoms only) caused by gram-negative coliforms is little influenced by the administration of antibiotics, no first choice of topical antibiotics are suggested in the AMCRA guidelines. By contrast, cases of severe mastitis (milk and udder abnormalities with symptoms of generalized disease) should be immediately treated with antimicrobials. TMP-SMX or the first generation cephalosporins, cefalexin or cefazolin, are first choice antimicrobials. As shown in Figure 49, occurrence of clinical resistance of <i>E. coli</i> isolated from mammary samples of diseased cattle is most common for TMP-SMX (minimum 7.3% (82/1110) in 2017, maximum 12.1% (82/678) in 2022). TMP-SMX is also the most common resistance observed in subclinical cases (Figure 49B). Resistance to amoxicillin-clavulanic acid (recommended as an intramammary (local) preparation as a second choice antimicrobial) increased over the study period (from 3.3% in 2014 (19/584 isolates) to 6.2% (42/678 isolates) in 2022)."

